 how early industry participants focused on creating and monetizing digital personal brands as a means of exerting control over their professional destinies in a time of acute economic uncertainty. Over time, their activities coalesced into an industry whose impact has reached far beyond the dreams of its progenitors—and beyond their control. Hund illustrates how the methods they developed for creating, monetizing, and marketing social media content have permeated our lives and untangles the unforeseen cultural and economic costs.The Influencer Industry reveals how, in an increasingly fractured and profit-driven communications environment, the people we think of as “real” are merely those who have learned to exploit the industry’s ever-shifting constructions of authenticity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aAuthenticity (Philosophy). 0aCommunication in marketing. 0aInfluence (Psychology). 0aInternet marketing. 0aInternet personalities. 0aSocial mediaxEconomic aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aAbsolute value.  aActivation.  aAfterhyperpolarization.  aAnonymity.  aAssociation of National Advertisers.  aBeauty.  aBig business.  aBlog.  aBusiness ethics.  aBusiness guru.  aCapacitor.  aCations, Divalent.  aChlorine.  aCircular orbit.  aCommodification.  aCommon knowledge.  aCommunity leader.  aCompany.  aConformational change.  aConjunction (astronomy).  aConstant term.  aCyberspace.  aDark matter.  aDedoose.  aDirect marketing.  aEconomic power.  aElectronic circuit.  aElementary particle.  aEmail.  aEmployment.  aEstimation.  aEva Chen.  aFacebook.  aFinance.  aFreelancers Union.  aGmax.  aGoogle News.  aHair care.  aHarvard Business School.  aImmigration.  aIndustry.  aInfluencer marketing.  aInformation 